The problem in the provided program is that it's trying to access a list el
element at an index that doesn't exist, specifically the fourth (index=3) e
element. The length of this "scores" list is only three elements long.

To fix the bug, you should change the line:
```Tundra
return scores[3];
```
to 
```Tundra
return scores[2]; // indexing starts at 0, so third element has an index of
of 2.
```
Entire corrected code is as follows:
```Tundra
def chooseBest(scores) {
  return scores[2];
}

val row = {
  name: "Ada",
  scores: [7, 8, 9]
};

val best = chooseBest(row.scores);
print(best); // This will print '9' as the expected output.
```
